Fumo offered a delightful dining experience that I highly recommend. From their service, to their food and atmosphere, everything was absolutely enjoyable.  Check-In: I was immediately acknowledged by the host upon arriving, and immediately seated. They do get very busy so (depending on the party size) they tell you there is a maximum amount of time at the table, although I sat over the time and they didn’t rush me out or even ask for the table back.  Service: Service was attentive, the server took my order and consistently checked in throughout the rest of my stay.  Food & Drinks: They have various options in their menu, I opted for their Brick Oven Pizza which I heard great things about, and boy am I glad I ordered one. It’s officially my favorite pizza in the area now. The flavors mesh together so well, especially when paired with a nice glass of wine. The pizza was a perfect balance of crunchy and creamy, and the Montepulciano was bold and rich. I also ordered the Panna Cotta, although it didn’t quite taste like a normal Panna Cotta, I have to admit it was absolutely delish. It did have a strong taste of vanilla bean, and had a thicker custard consistency than what Panna Cotta tends to be, but again it was very tasty (however, if you don’t like vanilla bean flavored items then this wouldn’t be for you). I accompanied my dessert with a glass of the Friulano which was also tasty and refreshing.  Price: Compared to other Italian restaurants in NYC, the pricing at Fumo is quite fair. They have wines ranging from $10-13, beers from $6-8, and cocktails at $13. Also, for the quality of food you’re getting I think the prices are definitely fair, especially when compared to other Italian restaurants in proximity.  Atmosphere: The place is located on Amsterdam Avenue, right across from City College, which is a beautiful campus with beautifully designed buildings therefore it’s an enjoyable sight, especially if seated alone. The vibe of the place is very calm and relaxed, perfect for a date, family dinner or intimate gather with friends or others. I also did notice they have heat lamps, so the place is already highly cozy without them, now I can only imagine during the cooler nights it’ll be cozier with those around.  Overall: Absolutely, I recommend this place. It is a must try; also heard their pastas are just as delicious as their pizzas.

A Disservice to Humankind  This food was a waste of time, money, energy, and enthusiasm. I moved into a new apartment today. Exhausted, I decided to treat myself to a $42 indulgence from Fumo via Grubhub. This was my experience: I opened the Chicken Parmesan and poised my knife to cut it. It didn't. I proceeded to saw away at the leather-like flap of chicken before taking a bite. It was so hard to cut, and I so ravenous, that I picked it up with my hands to take my next bite. However, since they didn't provide napkins, and I didn't have any unpacked to access, I decided to put the chicken down and keep sawing at it. The chicken's breading was not burned, so it would seem that, rather than it being initially overcooked, it was prepared far in advance and left to toughen and shrivel in a warming pan for who knows how long. The chicken sat on a bed of bland, glutinous, bloated penne. It had obviously been cooked in unsalted water, much earlier in the day, and held in oil, which effectively repelled the admittedly delicious marinara sauce from it.  As for my beverage of choice, I ordered a "can" of Malbec. This can was advertised as 12 oz. It was, in fact 8.5 oz. At first I was disappointed at the discrepancy, until I tasted it. I should have taken heed at the $6 price, but I foolishly trusted Fomo wouldn't lead me astray. That was a misapprehension. Grape juice with rubbing alcohol would have tasted very similar, I am sure.  On to the arugula salad (yes I ate it after the chicken, again, due to my ravenous state). It was pretty enough, with a generous portion of arugula encircled with shaved parmesan, one halved cherry tomato, and two thin apple slices. The salad was undressed. I found myself mentally yelling in Gordon Ramsay's voice, "It's not seasoned!"  After I worked my way about two-thirds through the salad, I found that it had been packaged by pouring olive oil in the bottom of the bowl and then piling the salad ingredients on top. Again, I was able to tell this had been done far in advance because the leaves that were in contact with the oil had absorbed it, leaving them translucent, dark green, and flapping about. I was glad to finally have at least the last third of my salad dressed. Perhaps unsalted, but at least with olive oil.  This was an utterly disappointing end to a long day of labor. I am incensed that this restaurant would pass off this garbage to people to eat. When I dine out, it is so I may enjoy food prepared skillfully and with love. Fumo was sorely lacking in both of these regards.
